findings.fix:
Pass the timestamp into rebuildIngredientExposuresForFoodLog from the caller site. For the add and update mutations the log's own timestamp is available in args.timestamp / record.timestamp. For backfill mutations, pass the log's timestamp (already available as log.timestamp in the loop). This makes all writes deterministic:

  await ctx.db.insert("ingredientExposures", {
    ...
    createdAt: args.timestamp,  // passed from caller
  });

Alternatively, accept that createdAt is an approximation and document it clearly, but the Convex docs explicitly state Date.now() must not be called inside query/mutation handlers.

findings.description:
Both replaceProfile (line 1059) and patchProfile (line 1163) contain:

  const updatedAt = args.now ?? Date.now();

The comment calls this a transitional fallback, but the fallback is still active and will be used by any caller that does not pass now. This is the same mutation-determinism violation as F002. If Convex replays the mutation and the caller did not pass now, the replayed transaction will compute a different updatedAt than the original.

findings.fix:
Throw on ownership mismatch instead of silently skipping:

  if (record.userId !== userId) {
    throw new Error("Not authorized to update log entry " + String(entry.id));
  }

If the batch semantics intentionally allow partial success (e.g. skipping missing rows), document that clearly and distinguish between "not found" skips and "not authorized" skips in the return value.

Add a guard at the top of the handler:

  if (args.startMs > args.endMs) {
    throw new Error("startMs must be <= endMs");
  }

Add a corresponding test case.

Add a timeout signal:

  const controller = new AbortController();
  const timeout = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), 8_000);
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url.toString(), {
      signal: controller.signal,
      headers: { "User-Agent": "PDH/1.0 (ingredient nutrition lookup)" },
    });
    ...
  } finally {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
  }

Also consider wrapping in a try/catch for AbortError and returning an empty array (not throwing) so the UI degrades gracefully.
